In Node.js, many core modules use error-first callbacks:
```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
fs.readFile('file.txt', (err, data) => {
  if (err) {
    console.error('Error reading file:', err);
    return;
  }
  console.log(data);
});
```
Always check `err` first; if it's truthy, handle it.

With `async/await`, you can use `try/catch` again:
```javascript
async function readFile() {
  try {
    const data = await fs.promises.readFile('file.txt');
    console.log(data);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('Error:', err);
  }
}
```

This is often the cleanest way.

Always handle promise rejections. As a last resort, you can listen for unhandled rejections:
```javascript
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason, promise) => {
  console.error('Unhandled Rejection at:', promise, 'reason:', reason);
  // Application specific logging or exit
});
```

In modern Node, unhandled rejections will terminate the process in the future, so always catch them.
